class Employee
{
private:
    string name;

public:
    Employee(string n) : name(n) {}

    Employee& operator*()
    {
        return *this;
    }

    Employee* operator->()
    {
        return this;
    }

    void display() const
    {
        cout << "Employee: " << name << endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    employee ob("pavan");

    (*ob).display();
    ob->display();
}

why not *ob.display()************VVVVIMP
Why?

The . (member access) operator has higher precedence than the unary * operator.

So the compiler interprets:

*ob.display();

as

*(ob.display());

It first tries to call:

ob.display();

which returns void.

Then it becomes:



*(void);

which is invalid.


(*ob).display();

is required because '.' has higher precedence than '*'.

If we write:

*ob.display();

the compiler interprets it as:

*(ob.display());

which is invalid because display() returns void.

Therefore we write:

(*ob).display();

This first calls operator*(), then invokes display() on the returned object.
